Here are all the configuration options available for the JWT client:

## JWTPro Configuration Options

```typescript
const client = new JWTPro({
  // Required
  baseUrl: 'https://your-wordpress-site.com/wp-json',

  // Optional - API Endpoints
  authNamespace: 'jwt-auth/v1',        // Default: 'jwt-auth/v1'
  wpApiNamespace: 'wp/v2',             // Default: 'wp/v2'

  // Optional - Token Storage
  tokenStorageStrategy: 'localStorage', // Options: 'localStorage', 'sessionStorage', 'memory', or custom ITokenStorageStrategy

  // Optional - Auto Refresh (currently not implemented)
  autoRefreshToken: false,             // Default: false
  refreshThreshold: 300,               // Default: 300 seconds

  // Optional - Custom Storage Keys  
  storageKeys: {
    accessToken: 'my_access_token',    // Default: 'jwt_access_token'
    refreshToken: 'my_refresh_token',  // Default: 'jwt_refresh_token'  
    userData: 'my_user_data'           // Default: 'jwt_user_data'
  },

  // Optional - Custom Logger
  logger: {
    debug: (msg, ...args) => console.debug(msg, ...args),
    info: (msg, ...args) => console.info(msg, ...args),
    warn: (msg, ...args) => console.warn(msg, ...args),
    error: (msg, ...args) => console.error(msg, ...args)
  }
});
```

**Key Options:**
- **`baseUrl`** (required): Your WordPress site's REST API base URL
- **`tokenStorageStrategy`**: Where to store tokens (browser: localStorage/sessionStorage, Node.js: memory)
- **`storageKeys`**: Customize storage key names to avoid conflicts
- **`authNamespace`**: Change if using custom JWT plugin endpoints
- **`logger`**: Custom logging implementation

